  "prompt": "How can I use the Wi-Fi on my windows phone (wp8.1) in BHU (hostels, departments, library)?",
  "response": "Using Wi-Fi on your Windows Phone 8.1 in BHU (Banaras Hindu University) requires understanding the available networks, authentication procedures, and possible issues. Here's a breakdown:\n\n**1. Identifying Available Wi-Fi Networks:**\n\n*   **BHU Networks:** Look for Wi-Fi networks with names like:\n    *   \"BHU-WiFi\"\n    *   \"BHU Students\"\n    *   \"BHU Guest\" (May be for temporary access only)\n    *   Department-specific networks (e.g., \"DeptOfCompSci\" - Ask your department for details)\n    *   Hostel-specific networks (e.g., \"HostelA-WiFi\" - Ask your warden/hostel authorities)\n*   **Private Networks:** There might be private Wi-Fi routers installed by individuals or shops nearby.  These may require a password that you'd have to ask them for.\n\n**2. Connecting to the Wi-Fi Network (General Steps):**\n\n1.  **Open Settings:** On your Windows Phone, swipe down from the top of the screen to open the Action Center, then tap \"All settings\" or go to the Start Screen and find the \"Settings\" app.\n\n2.  **Wi-Fi Settings:** In the Settings menu, tap \"Wi-Fi.\"\n\n3.  **Enable Wi-Fi:**  Make sure the Wi-Fi toggle is switched \"On.\" Your phone will start scanning for available networks.\n\n4.  **Select a Network:** From the list of available networks, tap on the BHU network you want to connect to (e.g., \"BHU-WiFi,\" \"BHU Students,\" etc.).\n\n5.  **Enter Credentials (if required):**  This is the crucial part. Depending on the network, you might be prompted for:\n    *   **Password (WEP/WPA/WPA2):**  This is the simplest case. Get the password from the network administrator (hostel warden, department head, or BHU IT support).\n    *   **BHU ID and Password (Most Likely):**  BHU usually uses a centralized authentication system.  You'll need your BHU student ID or employee ID and the corresponding password (which is also used for your BHU email/portal access).  The login page usually appears in your phone's browser.\n    *   **Username/Password and a specific security type (like PEAP or EAP-TLS):** This requires more advanced configuration.  You will need specific instructions from the BHU IT department.  This is less common but possible.\n\n**3. Browser Redirection and Login Portal (Common Scenario):**\n\n1.  **Connect to the Wi-Fi:** As mentioned above, select the BHU Wi-Fi network and if asked, enter any initial credentials.\n\n2.  **Open a Browser:**  Open your web browser (Internet Explorer on Windows Phone 8.1).\n\n3.  **Automatic Redirection:**  In most cases, your browser will automatically redirect you to a login portal page (a web page hosted by BHU's network).  If it doesn't redirect automatically:\n    *   Try typing a simple web address like `http://example.com` or `http://neverssl.com` into the address bar.  This should force the redirection.\n    *   Clear your browser cache and cookies if redirection still doesn't happen.\n\n4.  **Enter Credentials on the Portal:**  On the login portal page, you'll typically find fields for:\n    *   **Username:** Enter your BHU ID (e.g., 12345678)\n    *   **Password:** Enter your BHU password (the same one you use for your BHU email/portal).\n\n5.  **Submit:** Click the \"Login\" or \"Submit\" button on the portal.\n\n6.  **Successful Login:** If your credentials are correct, you should be logged in, and your browser should redirect to a success page or the URL you originally requested.  You can now browse the internet.\n\n**4. Important Considerations and Troubleshooting:**\n\n*   **BHU IT Support:** The best resource for definitive Wi-Fi access instructions is the BHU IT support department.  They will have the most up-to-date information and can help you troubleshoot specific issues. Find their contact information on the BHU website or by asking in your department/hostel.\n*   **Registration:** Sometimes, you might need to *register* your device (MAC address) with the BHU IT department before you can use the Wi-Fi. This is a security measure. Ask about the device registration process. You can find your phone's MAC address in Settings > about > More info.\n*   **Time Limits and Quotas:** BHU might have time limits or data quotas on its Wi-Fi network. Be aware of these restrictions.\n*   **Poor Signal Strength:**  Wi-Fi signal strength can vary greatly depending on your location within BHU.  Try moving to a different spot to improve the signal.\n*   **Network Congestion:** During peak hours (evenings, weekends), the network might be congested, leading to slow speeds.\n*   **Proxy Settings:**  BHU might use a proxy server for internet access.  In your Windows Phone's Wi-Fi settings (after connecting to the network), there might be an option for proxy settings.  You'll need to get the proxy server address and port number from BHU IT support. However, proxy usage is less common now.\n*   **Captive Portal Issues:** Sometimes the captive portal login page might not load correctly due to browser compatibility issues or network problems. Try the following:\n    *   Clear your browser's cache and cookies.\n    *   Restart your phone.\n    *   Try a different browser if available (though options are limited on WP8.1).\n    *   Disable any VPN or proxy settings temporarily.\n    *   Ensure your phone's date and time are correct.\n*   **802.1X Authentication Issues:** If the network uses 802.1X (e.g., PEAP, EAP-TLS), you'll need to configure the Wi-Fi settings on your phone carefully. This usually involves selecting the correct security protocol, authentication method, and possibly installing a root certificate. Get the exact instructions from BHU IT.\n*   **Check the WiFi Standards supported on your Windows Phone:** Your phone is old so it might not support newer WiFi standards and hence have issues.\n*   **Consider a Mobile Hotspot:** If you have a mobile data plan on your phone, you can create a mobile hotspot to share your data with other devices. This may be a solution if the BHU WiFi is unreliable.\n\n**Example (Likely Scenario):**\n\n1.  Go to Settings > Wi-Fi and turn on Wi-Fi.\n2.  Select \"BHU-WiFi\" or \"BHU Students.\"\n3.  Open Internet Explorer.\n4.  You'll be redirected to the BHU Wi-Fi login portal.\n5.  Enter your BHU ID in the \"Username\" field.\n6.  Enter your BHU password in the \"Password\" field.\n7.  Click \"Login.\"\n\n**Key Takeaway:**\n\nAlways consult the BHU IT support department for the most accurate and up-to-date instructions for connecting to the Wi-Fi network.  They are the best resource for resolving any connectivity issues. Good luck!\n",
